<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: FORMER EDUCATOR TO RUN FOR COLLEGE BOARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saying the district needs tighter fiscal control and better access to its 
managers, former educator John Tallman said Monday that he will run for a seat 
on the Ventura County Community College District's Board of Trustees. 
</P>
<P>
 Tallman, who worked as a teacher and vice chancellor at Ventura College for 
more than 20 years, said he will try to beat out incumbent Karen Boone in Area 
1 on the fall ballot. 
</P>
<P>
 "The decision-making process could be better," said Tallman, a Ventura 
resident who retired last year. "Faculty voices aren't heard at all, and some 
people are intimidated from speaking. Therefore, the best decisions are not 
always made." 
</P>
<P>
 Tallman, 64, said the district "is fiscally fragile and unstable due to poor 
income projections and lack of awareness of changing conditions" in the funding 
processes. 
</P>
<P>
 "The district badly needs a trustee with an understanding of community college 
finance," said Tallman, who spent one year as chief fiscal officer at Ventura 
College. 
</P>
<P>
 Boone, appointed to the board in 1992 when Gregory Kampf resigned, has already 
said she would seek election. 
</P>
<P>
 The four-week filing period for candidates opens July 18. JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</TEXT>
