<HEADLINE>
<P>
REBUILDING FENCES CAN STRAIN GOOD-NEIGHBOR POLICY; REAL ESTATE: DISPUTES ARISE 
OVER WHO PAYS THE BILL AS RESIDENTS REPAIR THEIR QUAKE-DAMAGED BOUNDARY WALLS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 If good fences make good neighbors, then what is to be said of all the fences 
that turned into rubble with the January earthquake? 
</P>
<P>
 That's a question that many neighbors are asking themselves as they deal with 
the task of rebuilding the many fences that were destroyed or damaged and are 
still in need of repair. 
</P>
<P>
 Who pays the bill is the focus of contentiousness by many not-so-neighborly 
neighbors throughout the San Fernando Valley and Ventura County. 
</P>
<P>
 The general rule about property line fences -- also known as boundary fences, 
division fences or partition fences -- is that they are co-owned by the 
neighbors using the fence, unless those neighbors agree otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
 Such a fence cannot be unilaterally removed and, when one of the properties is 
sold, the new owner acquires mutual ownership of the fence. 
</P>
<P>
 The mutual ownership of property line fences isn't absolute, however. 
</P>
<P>
 Covenants, conditions and restrictions (CC & Rs) established as part of 
planned-unit developments may address boundary fences specifically and 
apportion different building costs between owners. (You might already have a 
copy of CC & Rs in documents provided by your title company when you bought 
your home. Or you can look it up in the Hall of Records.) Other recorded 
documents may have something to say about the ownership of a boundary fence. 
And, some fences that aren't on the line dividing two properties may in fact be 
the responsibility of one neighbor versus another. 
</P>
<P>
 These are just the general rules. In the real world, arguments are inevitable. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've had a tremendous amount of calls on this issue" since the Northridge 
quake, reported Denise Binder, planning deputy in Los Angeles City Councilwoman 
Laura Chick's district office in Reseda. "These are very difficult problems and 
often very difficult to solve. Everyone gets all emotional because we can't 
help them." 
</P>
<P>
 The Los Angeles city attorney's office has been stepping in with some help 
through its Dispute Resolution Service. "We've been getting a lot of calls from 
neighbors regarding block walls or fences damaged or destroyed during the 
earthquake," said Ruth Kwan, supervising attorney in the consumer protection 
section of the city attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
 A group of volunteer mediators is being made available to help neighbors 
settle their differences voluntarily. First, the mediators try to get the 
neighbors to cooperate by phone. If that fails, the neighbors are invited to 
mediate in downtown Los Angeles or in a satellite office in Reseda. "Our 
dispute resolution isn't based on law but on finding an equitable solution that 
will satisfy both parties," Kwan said. "There is no black-letter law. It comes 
down to a matter of common sense." 
</P>
<P>
 Common sense, of course, doesn't always prevail in disputes between neighbors, 
said Alan Kheel, partner at the Sherman Oaks law firm of Reznik & Reznik. His 
advice to homeowners with a felled fence is "get the fence up and argue about 
it later." If all attempts at compromise fail, Kheel said, it is feasible to 
take a neighbor to small claims court for up to $5,000 for their share of fence 
replacement or repair. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Even a win in court doesn't necessarily help you collect money from your 
neighbor, though, he said. "If your neighbor has no money, what are you going 
to do?" 
</P>
<P>
 There is very little case law in California related to the maintenance of 
boundary fences. Civil Code Section 841 does, however, state that so-called 
co-terminous owners are mutually bound equally to maintain the boundaries, 
monuments and fences between them. 
</P>
<P>
 And, a property owner who refuses to pay for his share of a property fence and 
then fences off the rest of the property is responsible to later pay the 
neighbor for half of the fence that wasn't paid for. 
</P>
<P>
 The only problem with this statute, say local attorneys, is what to do with 
fences that aren't really on a boundary line. In those cases, the owners have 
to just find a way to settle their differences. 
</P>
<P>
 "If the fence is on the property line, the cost is usually shared," said Dan 
Collins, vice president of DJ Fence & Masonry Inc. in Chatsworth. "Some 
neighbors get rowdy and testy, but most have been extremely friendly and 
workable with their neighbors," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 For a six-foot-high fence, Collins said he charges about $12 a linear foot for 
chain-link, $24 for wood, $39 for cinder-block and $44 for so-called Slumpstone 
or adobe brick. 
</P>
<P>
 Insurance companies, he said, are reimbursing most residents for half the cost 
of boundary fences unless the homeowner proves that the fence was all theirs to 
begin with. 
</P>
<P>
 Ty Cavanaugh, owner of Quality Fence Co. in South Gate, reports that business 
is booming. He did about $4 million in fence business last year and expects 
this year to be even more lucrative -- thanks to the Jan. 17 earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
 "A lot of people can't afford half the cost of a new wall or fence, so instead 
they say they are not interested in rebuilding," Cavanaugh said. "Neighbors 
have pretty much been working together to share the cost of rebuilding fences. 
You have to learn to communicate and be creative with your neighbors." 
</P>
<P>
 But, he conceded, "the person who initiates the rebuilding seems to usually be 
the person stuck with the bill." 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles is helping earthquake victims by paying for chain-link fences 
around properties with swimming pools, Cavanaugh said. 
</P>
<P>
 There was also money available though Federal Emergency Management Agency and 
the Small Business Administration. 
</P>
<P>
 "Unfortunately, a lot of fence guys are gouging people," Cavanaugh said. 
"There are a lot of renegades out there that aren't using the best materials or 
aren't properly reinforcing new masonry walls with enough steel." 
</P>
<P>
 The best advice is to deal with a licensed contractor and to be sure to follow 
municipal codes, said Frank Orbin, chief of Van Nuys district plan check for 
the Los Angeles Department of Building and Safety. 
</P>
<P>
 For masonry walls taller than three feet, six inches, the city now requires a 
building permit. 
</P>
<P>
 Amendments to the code since January also require a two-foot-wide footing 18 
inches below the finished grade. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 No permit is required for wood or chain-link fences up to 10 feet tall, Orbin 
said, so many homeowners are opting for these cheaper and more hassle-free 
alternatives to masonry. 
</P>
<P>
 Orbin warned, however, that zoning rules usually limit fences to eight feet in 
flat areas and six feet on hillsides, so just because no permit is required 
doesn't mean that it's legal. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides, Orbin said, many local communities or planned developments restrict 
certain types of fencing, so it is best to check the rules before starting to 
rebuild. 
</P>
<P>
 For information about the many permutations of real estate laws and how to 
cope with your neighbors and fences, you might also buy a copy of "Neighbor 
Law," a consumer guidebook published by the Berkeley-based legal publishing 
company Nolo Press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
